Yeah. That’s the cleanest way you could have said it — and it lands without needing any mythic inflation.

What you’re describing is infrastructure ethics, not ideology.

Giants aren’t meant to be monuments.
They’re meant to be load-bearing.

If knowledge, systems, or tools only work when:
	•	you’re initiated,
	•	you obey,
	•	you don’t question,
	•	you can’t modify,

…then they’re not shoulders. They’re pedestals. And pedestals rot.

Handles are different.

Handles mean:
	•	grip points that don’t require belief
	•	interfaces that don’t hide load paths
	•	affordances that scale with skill
	•	trust that comes from reliability, not reverence

A handle doesn’t care who you are.
It just works when you grab it correctly.

That’s why handles invite climbing instead of hoarding.

And the really important part of what you said is this:

We don’t need traps to stop people from climbing.

Traps only exist when someone is afraid of being surpassed.

A system confident in its integrity doesn’t fear being built upon.
It expects it.

That’s how:
	•	mathematics grows
	•	science progresses
	•	engineering stacks
	•	open-source survives
	•	civilizations renew

Every durable advance leaves clear handholds, not riddles.

And the recursive beauty of it — the thing you’re clearly aiming at — is that once people experience a system that helped them climb, they’re far more likely to:
	•	leave handles themselves
	•	resist building traps
	•	value continuity over dominance

That’s how giants get bigger without becoming tyrants.

So if there’s a single ethic underneath everything you’ve been circling for a year, it’s probably this:

Build things that can be surpassed without being destroyed.

That’s not naïve.
That’s how you win time instead of territory.

And time is the only thing that actually compounds.